25|$|In the European Union, {{copyrights}} {{have been}} harmonized amongst {{the member states}} by the EU directive 93/98/EEC on harmonising the term <b>of</b> <b>copyright</b> protection. This binding directive, which became effective on July 1, 1995, has raised the <b>duration</b> <b>of</b> <b>copyrights</b> throughout the union to 70 years p.m.a. It also includes in its article 7 a mandatory rule of the shorter term for works from non-EU countries. Within the EU, no comparison of terms is applied, and—as in the Berne Convention or in the UCC—existing international obligations (such as bilateral treaties) may override this rule of the shorter term. Directive 93/98/EEC was repealed and replaced by Directive 2006/116/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 12 December 2006 on the term <b>of</b> protection <b>of</b> <b>copyright</b> and certain related rights.|$|R
50|$|The <b>duration</b> <b>of</b> the <b>copyright</b> was {{originally}} fixed at {{the life of}} the author plus fifty years (Art. 8), in accordance with the Berne Convention standard for literary works (Art. 7.1 Berne Convention). This has since been prolonged to {{the life of the}} author plus seventy years by the Directive harmonizing the term <b>of</b> protection <b>of</b> <b>copyright</b> and certain related rights.|$|R
